Data dictionary

Here is a data dictionary for the museums dataset:

  • ****: Data Dictionary
  • name: a character variable giving the full proper name of the art museum
  • country: a character variable giving the country of location of the restaurant as Country
  • city: a character variable giving the city of location of the restaurant as City
  • visitors_2016: numeric number of people that visited the an specific art museum during the year 2016. Use only whole numbers. If less than 1, round down to zero.
  • visitors_2015: numeric number of people that visited the an specific art museum during the year 2016. Use only whole numbers. If less than 1, round down to zero. size: a categorical variable describing the size of the art museum. Possible options are:
  • Small
  • Medium:
  • Large:
  • year_established: numeric number describing the year the art gallery was established. Format as YYYY with the four digit year.
  • metro_access: a categorical variable explaining the accessibility of the art museum via subway. Possible options are: Yes, No
  • public: a categorical variable distinguishing if the art museum is publically owned. If yes, the art museum is owned by a government entity or accessible to the public with no charge. Possible options are: Yes, No .

Which can be read in as follows:

YOU SHOULD UPLOAD THE FINAL DATASET AS A CSV FILE TO GITHUB, THEN FILL IN THE INFORMATION HERE (MAKE SURE TO CHANGE THE NAME OF THE DATANAME TO SOMETHING REASONABLE AND FOLLOWING OUR NAMING CONVENTIONS):

museums <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/URstats/stat209-s18-andreacelleri/master/project_a_data.csv")

Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  name = col_character(),
  country = col_character(),
  city = col_character(),
  visitors_2016 = col_integer(),
  visitors_2015 = col_integer(),
  size = col_character(),
  year_established = col_integer(),
  metro_access = col_character(),
  public = col_character()
)

Exploratory Analysis

NOW, IN ABOUT 2-3 PARAGRAPHS ALONG WITH A COUPLE OF EMBEDDED GRAPHS, EXPLORE A POTENTIALLY INTERESTING RELATIONSHIP IN THE DATASET. MAKE SURE THAT THE CODE TO CONSTRUCT THE PLOTS IS NOT INCLUDED IN THE REPORT. ALSO MAKE SURE THAT THE PLOTS ARE WOVEN INTO THE ANALYSIS AND NOT JUST DUMPED AT THE START OR END OF THE SECTION

ggplot(museums, aes(visitors_2016,size)) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x="Visitors", y="Size of Museum", title="Relationship between Size of Museum and Visitors")
